llm_step:
In Figure $n$, there are $n$ equilateral triangles along the bottom.  Therefore, Figure 3 has 3 equilateral triangles along the bottom, and Figure 25 has 25 equilateral triangles along the bottom.

[asy]
unitsize(0.2 cm);

int i;

draw((0,0)--(2,0)--(1,sqrt(3))--cycle);

for (i = 1; i <= 24; ++i) {
  draw((i,-i*sqrt(3))--(i + 2,-i*sqrt(3))--(i + 1,-(i - 1)*sqrt(3))--cycle);
}

draw((25,-25*sqrt(3))--(27,-25*sqrt(3))--(26,-24*sqrt(3))--cycle);

label("Figure 3", (1,-3*sqrt(3)), N);
label("Figure 25", (26,-28*sqrt(3)), N);
[/asy]

The length of each side of the equilateral triangle in Figure 3 is $\frac{7s}{3}$, where $s$ is the length of each segment.  Therefore, the length of each side of the equilateral triangle in Figure 25 is $\frac{25s}{3}$.

[asy]
unitsize(0.2 cm);

int i;

draw((0,0)--(2,0)--(1,sqrt(3))--cycle);

for (i = 1; i <= 24; ++i) {
  draw((i,-i*sqrt(3))--(i + 2,-i*sqrt(3))--(i + 1,-(i - 1)*sqrt(3))--cycle);
}

draw((25,-25*sqrt(3))--(27,-25*sqrt(3))--(26,-24*sqrt(3))--cycle);

label("$\frac{7s}{3}$", (1,sqrt(3)/2), W);
label("$\frac{25s}{3}$", (26,-24*sqrt(3)/2), E);
[/asy]

Therefore, the number of segments in Figure 25 is $3 \cdot \frac{25s}{3} = \boxed{25s}$.

