We can solve this problem using complementary counting. The probability that segments $AB$ and $CD$ do not intersect is the same as the probability that $A$ and $B$ are on one side of the line containing segment $CD.$ Without loss of generality, assume that $C$ is at the point $(1,0)$ on the unit circle. Then $D$ is at the point $(\cos\theta,\sin\theta)$ for some $0\leq\theta<2\pi.$

[asy]
import olympiad; import geometry; size(100); defaultpen(linewidth(0.8));
draw(Circle(origin,1));
pair C=(1,0),D=dir(60);
draw(C--D);
label("$C$",C,SE); label("$D$",D,N);
[/asy]

The line containing segment $CD$ is then $y=\tan\theta\cdot(x-1).$ If $A$ is on one side of this line, then $B$ must be on the other side. Without loss of generality, assume that $A$ is at the point $(\cos\alpha,\sin\alpha)$ for some $0\leq\alpha<2\pi.$ Then $B$ is on the other side of the line if and only if $\tan\alpha>\tan\theta.$

[asy]
import olympiad; import geometry; size(100); defaultpen(linewidth(0.8));
draw(Circle(origin,1));
pair C=(1,0),D=dir(60);
draw(C--D);
label("$C$",C,SE); label("$D$",D,N);
draw((0,0)--dir(120),dashed);
label("$\theta$",(0,0.2),NE);
draw((0,0)--C--dir(120),dashed);
label("$\alpha$",(0.5,0.2),NE);
[/asy]

Since $\tan$ is an increasing function on the interval $[0,\pi/2),$ the probability that $\tan\alpha>\tan\theta$ is $\frac{1}{2}.$ Therefore, the probability that segments $AB$ and $CD$ do not intersect is $\frac{1}{2},$ and the probability that they do intersect is $1-\frac{1}{2}=\boxed{\frac{1}{2}}.$

