We can solve this problem by dividing the rectangle into four congruent rectangles, as shown below. [asy]
size(200);
draw((-250,100)--(250,100)--(250,-100)--(-250,-100)--cycle);
draw((0,100)--(0,-100),dashed);
draw((-250,0)--(250,0),dashed);
label("$O$",(0,0),N);
label("$A$",(-250,100),NW); label("$B$",(250,100),NE); label("$C$",(250,-100),SE); label("$D$",(-250,-100),SW);
[/asy] Let $P$ be the point we choose, and let $x$ and $y$ be the distances from $P$ to the horizontal and vertical sides of the rectangle, respectively. Then $x$ and $y$ are both between 0 and 50, and $P$ is closer to $O$ than to any of the vertices if and only if $x < 25$ and $y < 25$. Thus, the probability we seek is the area of the square with vertices $(0,0)$ and $(25,25)$ divided by the area of the rectangle, which is $50k$. Therefore, the probability is $\frac{25^2}{50k} = \boxed{\frac{1}{2k}}$.

